{"/service/ndnp/deu/batch_deu_flash_ver01/data/sn87062224/00514156736/1949061001/0357.xml":{"full_text":"_\nDELAWARE'S LEADING weekly NEWSPAPER\nThe Milford Chronicle is Delaware's largest vreekly\nB BS\u00ab y\u00e6? aA'S.-'JW\u00c6'S' ftsaffiy.\nsen ted each issue. All advertising\"^ sold on a baa 1 \u00bbof a\ncirculation ot cr t.ooo cic. ,ch\nsembly has closed, for which we are all more\nthan thankful. They are gone after five\nmonths of wrangling, double dealing and\n\nremember them when you start to pay the\ngreatly increased income taxes, which em\nployers will be compelled to withhold from\npayrolls beginning July 1st. You'll be re\nmembering them when you dig into your\npockets to pay the new cigarette and cigai\ntaxes. You'll remember ahd cuss them when\nMILFORD CHRONICLE\nESTABLISHED OCTOBER 4, 1878\nTHEO. TOWNSEND\nEditor and Proprietor from 1878 to 1910\nMILFORD CHRONICLE PUBLISHING COMPANY\n10 TO 1\u00ab BOOTH WEST FRONT STREET\nMILFORD. DELAWARE\nPUBLISHERS\n_President\n_Vice-President\n.Secretary-Treasurer\n3. Marshall Townsend.\nVirginia 8. Townsend.\nTheodore Townsend\u2014\n_Editor\nManaging Editor\nS;\nMarshall Townsend\nobert H. Yerkea\nBsolusive National Advertising Representative\nGreater Weeklies\nMew York Chicago Detroit Philadelphia\nSubscription Terms\nMall\u2014In Delaware, ta.ro i\nYear\nOutside et Del\u00e0 wate. $3.00 a Year\nJive Cents\nSingle Copl\nI\n\u2022PHONES 19 and 20\u2014MILFORD _\nAddress all communications to the Milford Chronicle\nPublishing Company. Milford. Delaware\nSntmd sa second-claw matter March 3, HU at the\npostoffice at Milford. Del., under Act of March 3. 1ST\u00bb\nMEMBER OF THF. ASSOCIATED PRESS\nThe Associated Press is entitled exclusively to the use\nfor republication of all the local news printed In this news\npaper. as well as all AP news dispatches\nFRIDAY, JUNE 10, 1949\nGONE\u2014 BUT YOU WILL BE\nREMEMBERING THEM\nThe 115th Session.of the General As\njust plain disregard for the public in gen\neral. Gone they are\u2014but you'll be renum\nbering them for a long, long t\u00ffne. You'll\nyou pay your increased gasoline taxes. You'll\nremember.\nAnd many, many Of you elated school tea\nrhpr\u00ab will rempmhpr tbpm to vour sorrow\n\u25a0SPSS, Zl a R rio-Rf\nYou ll get the increased increments all right\n\u2014for a time. That time won t be too far off\neither. The reason for the increase, whether\nit has dawned on you or not, was to secure\nou b \u00c6 X\u00ceT T^/additional toney \"will\nmake you fight hard to hold your job against\nthose who wt apply. You are in for future\ntrouble. You'll remember them. You prop\nerty owners and tax payers will remember\nil' nv, Itmu rmu'll voninmW tlinm tritmi\nthem. Oh, how you 11 lemember them when\nextra assessments are necessary to retire\nbonds which have been authorized for public\nP ..J. JJ .V. 11 fu- V i p\nbuildings and additional highway programs.\nYou'll remember them. And the adminis\ntration at Dover will be remembered. How\nit will be remembered. You voted for ifiast\nfall And oh how von trot it You'll not for\nY\nget this group for years\u2014your tax bills will*\nbe the reminder.\nA SESSION OF CONTRASTS\nThe General Assembly iust ended has\nbeen from the beirimfimr one U of contrasts\u2014\noeen irom me Beginning one oi contrasts\u00bb\ngreat contrasts. Competent business men\nand responsible citizens inexperienced in\nlegislative procedure following blindly with\nout any leadership. Likable fellows led to\nthe slaughter of public oponion. The first\nNegro to sit in a Delaware General Assem\nbly conducting himself and legislating for\nthe public good to such an extent that he\nwas an outstanding member of the House of\nRepresentatives. A man who was a credit to\nDelaware. Over in the Senate Delaware's\nfirst woman Senator battling it out with her\nparty and jumping the traces constantly,\nPraised by the Democrats whose program\nshe frequently supported. Disliked by her\nparty colleagues, she finishes her senate term\nin the midst of confusion and like and dis\nlike according to the individual's views. A\n\nlegislature that passed much progressive\nlegislation, and a group that went far too\nfar in taxation. An Assembly that started\nout in confusion and disorder and ended in\nbackroom conferences which many believe\nwas inspired to take care of the liquor in\nterests. Trades and trades, confusion and\ndisorder, tax and tax, failure to amend the\nover-stringent labor laws passed in 1947, a\nGeneral Assembly that pleased few, disgust\ned many, has passed into history. May its\nactions not.rise up to haunt us.\nThe closing days of the General Assem\nbly saw the passage of the Sewer Tax Bill\nwhich City Council sponsored. Under the\nprovisions of the charter amendment City\nCouncil is now authorized to levy a sewer\ntax each year up to 60% of the amount of the\nwater bill for each property within the city\nlimits. The. legislation also provides that\nthe monies derived from the sewer tax shall\nbe used for maintenance of sewers and the\nextension of new sewers throughout the city,\nA last minute Senate amendment to the or\niginal House Bill makes it mandatory for\nthe city to maintain at the cost of the city\nall lead-in sewers from the main sewer to\nthe curb line on every street. It further pro\nvides that if prompt repairs to clogged or\ndamaged sewers are not made within 48\nhours after the city office has been notified,\nthen the property owner may have the work\ndone at city expense, said costs to be deduct\ned from sewer taxes levied against the prop\nerty. This latter provision makes the City\nof Milford responsible for all sewers under\nthe streets of the town and it is the duty of\nthe city to repair any damages to the streets\nwhich may be incurred in making the sewer\nrepairs. The Charter amendment as finally\npassed is fair to every one concerned\u2014the\ncity and the property owner. It should\nmuch to eliminate delays in repairs and\nthe same time give the city needed funds\nwith which to build new sewer extensions.\nMILFORD'S SEWER TAX\n\n\nTRUMAN'S PROGRAM DOUBTFUL\nIt would have taken a super seer to have\nforecast, last November, that a Democratic\nPresident who had just won a stunning vic\ntory at the polls would have his legislative\nprogram knocked on the head in most par\nticulars by Congress. But that seems to be\nwhat has happened.\nLooking into the crystal ball, here is the\nstatus of his program at present.\nTaft-Hartley Act\u2014M r. Truman wants;\ncomplete repeal. It would require a miracle\nto aciheve it. It is doubtful if anything save\ntechnical changes in the law will be voted.\nIt may not be changed at all.\n$4,000,000,000 Tax Increase\never this comes up, a glacial atmosphere de\nscends on Congress. Everything will be done\nto avoid any tax increase. If, of dire neces\nsity, a tax bill is passed, it will be very dif- j\nferent from Mr. Truman's desire.\nExpanded Social Security\u2014T his is in\nthe doldrums. The section with the best\nchance Of approval Would give increased\nbenefits to the aged. Opposition to the Ad\nrninistration's medical proposals IS VCiy\n8 ra e measure pro\nposed by Senator Taft and others, has many\nmore adherents.\nColumbia Valley Authority\u2014T his is\nkey step in the Administration's plan for\nthe greatly expanding government power\ndevelopment and solidifying Federal author\nity over water and other natural resources\nof the nation. Cost would be some $2,000,\n000,000. Has small chance this session, will\nbe pushed hard again,\nStandby Authority for Price Con\ntrols, Allocations, etc. Absolutely dead.\nNew Farm Subsidy Plan\u2014T his is a\nscheme, suggested by Secretary Brannan,\nwhereby food prices to consumers would be\nheld down by giving direct Federal subsidies\nto farmers. The Congressional reception has\nbeen chilly.\nWhy should the President's program\nhave encountered such heavy going? There\nf 0 a g\"\"^^ n p\u20acC 1 Sl'y 1 Tthe\u00b0 IfrSt\u00ea,\nare conservatively inclined and have little\nuse for what is called the \"Tru-Deal\"\nWhen\n1\na\n__ t hey fear it would result in state socialism.\nSecond the President has antagonized some\n4-u p morp influential lawmakers bv what is\na u 4\ntheY re ^rd as a demanding, dictatoi lal at\ntitude. Third, the decline ip business, even\nthough it has been moderate, has developed\nattitude of watchful waiting, and Con\n^\"n't wanfto depress togs further\nselsion may tel. a different story\nthe p re ident is organizing for battle. But\nh making sma headway this time. c\n\n\nIRON-CLAD CENSORSHIP\nl\nUnder an order recently issued by the\nqwrptfil-v of Dpfpnsp tho most comnlete cen\nSec pv U..\nsorsmp yet Known in mis counuy U\ndissemination ot information Ot a militai y\ncharacter has been established.\nThe order established what is known as\n4 c r, TViic Branch\nthe Security Review Branch. This blanch\nIS given the power to review intormational\nmaterial of any nature from military sour\nees, and to decide what may be made public.\nThe military sources covered by the order\ninclude, along with regular military per\npjvilia\u00bb em r>lovees of the various y\njwmej. Civilian employees O^t me VMWUh\nbranches of military service, active reserve\npersonnel, retired military personnel, and\nsoon. The order even includes transci ipt of\ntestimony before committees of Congress in\nexecutive session by personnel subject to\nmilitary jurisdiction.\nAll of us realize the necessity tor guard\ning information which might be of value to\nforeign powers and which affects our na\ntional security. But that is a very different\nthing from the creation of an ail-powerfui\ncensorship board which,,if it so desires, can\nprevent any and all debate upon policy by\nthe people who know the most about it, and\nabolish informed criticism. If that happens,\nthe citizens of the country will know as\nmuch or as little about military affairs as\nthe Secretary of Defense permits,\nWriting in the Pensacola, Florida, Jour\nnal, George Dixon says of the order: \"Its net\neffect would seem to be as absolute as any\nthing ever issued by the Soviet cominform.\nCensorship of this kind should be repugnant\nto a free people,\n\nBACK OF MODERN RETAILING\nWhen we go shopping, most of us take\nit for granted that the stores will have what\nwe want. We may patronize chains, inde\npendents, or any other kind of retail outlet.\nWhatever the kind, we expect to find a wide\nselection of goods, intelligent salespeople, a\ncourteous welcome, and good service. That\nexpectation is usually justified.\nThe vanished crossroads emporium\ndidn't have to give much effort to pleasing\nthe customers\u2014it had a monopoly of the\nlocal business and people took what it offer\ned and paid the price or went without. Then,\nas the nation grew and transportation im\nproved, more stores were opened. Real com\npetition appeared. The inefficient merchant,\nor the merchant who wanted to earn an ex\ncessive profit, found that the going was get\nting tougher. The chains came along and\npioneered the idea of mass distribution with\na very small profit on each sale. The inde\npendents followed suit and met the new corn\npetition successfully.\nWe see the result today. The typical\nsmall town store carries the same kind of\ngoods that are found in huge metropolitan\nstores. Prices are about the same. Dis\nplays, service, and sanitation are compor\nable. And the reason for it is oempetition,\nwhich is the staunch protector of the con\nsumer's interest,\nStores of the future will be better than\nthose of today, just as those of today are\nbetter than those of the past. Merchants will\ncontinue to try to outdo the man next door,\nand to offer more inducements. And that\nwill work to the advantage of everyonp.\nPREVIEW OP SUMMER\nr\nv*.\n\n\n->-.4\n\nm\nCOM<5RE55\n4 Vi\n\u2022u\\-r\n\u25a0\u25a0j\nrs\nCL\nj\nI\nI\nH\n\nR\n9l\nv/\n\nrc\nwt\n\nm\nET'\n.\"VA\nA\nr\ntj\n5\u00ceS\nA\niJS..\nt\n\nI\nJ.\n0\n\n\nUJk\nWm\nv\nm\nV\nWA\nv\niit-V\n\nI\n,v\n'm\nAs Taken From The Files\nOf The Milford Chronicle\nThirty Years Ago\nMrs. Joseph hui of Philadelphia!\nVisiting friends and relatives in\nMilford. i\nH\nivi r()nt ramlations \u201e\u201eon the\n\u00eet\u00eefvii Sueiiter last sundav\nw\u00c4/p\u00bb v\u00c4t 1\nbeen 'dsltli.E Mr. and Mrs. P.\nR b,nion\n\nMr. and Mrs. Donohugh and Mrs.\nMary Hill of Philadelphia, spent\nweek-end with Mr. and Mrs.\nHaro i,i Donohueh\n\n\nMiss Irene Shirley of West Col\nlingswood. N. J.. visited her uncle,\nGeorge VV. Shirley of Causey ave\nnue over Decoration Day.\n\nThe Misses Edith and Alice Fra\nand James of rhiiadd-;new\nphia aro gpending commencement\nweek with Mrs. Mary A. Nutter. i\n\nFor the first lime since Hie war\nstarted .lie Alun.nl Associationithls\near entertained the graduating\nclass at a banquel in the New\nWindsor Hotel Those wh0 wlll re\nceive their diplomas this year are\n^orence Ellen dims .Flor\nence D \u00f4 uglas Gray, william Humes\nGrjer Mary 0smond Grlert Marga\nret Vaules Grier. Mildred Griffith.\nBlanche -arib^ w l P e r r Ir nd\nIris lreland> Virginia Wyatt Lynch!\nWilma Faye Moore, John Edward\nMurphy. Charles Armel Nutter,\nbert Bel1 i' ierce Ruth Anna Rus\nB\u00c4BSON Sounds Danger Signal\n\n\nNEVV YORK CITY. June 10\u2014\nDuring the twenty-eight, years\nthat I have been writing this\nweekly column. I have spldom\nfive million\nsuggested to my\nreaders that (hey write their\n1 am doing so\nCongressmen,\nnow. however, because of the\nindifference which I found as to\nGovernment finances on my re\ncent annual trip about the coun\ndifferent,\nj\nThe present danger is that Congress, to satisfy\nthose who are opposed to increased taxes and also\nthose who want to hold jobs for their friends, may\ncause the country to fall into the terrible and dang\nerous habit of deficit financing,\u2014that is. to run the\n1 Government at a loss and borrow money to make up\ntry.\nDEFICIT FINANCING\nRoger W. Babson\nFor the first time in. many\n(he Government has\npeace years\n\u25a0bed the \"parting of the ways\" in connection with\nthe budget. Of course, during the war it\nimpossible to balance the budget and no one\nasked (hat it he done; but today the situation is very\nThe country is now at peace; business is\nnd employment continues to be high.\nreat\nbalancing\nwas\nfairly good; a\nOn the other hand, due to the demands from abroad\nand the possibility of smaller income tax receipts,\nF, Klier laxes must\none of two things is necessary.\nhe increased, or Government expenses inn si be cor\nrespondingly reduced. The Hoover Commission rec\nommends an annual reduction of three billion.\n1 believe that President Truman is an honest man,\nbut I fear some of his advisors arc either misleading\nhim or else are ignorant of economic truths. He\nwants a balanced budget, but he seems unwilling to\nbalance this budget in the obvious and sensible way,\n\u2014namely by reducing Government expenses. This\nwould be the natural way for any business to bal\nance its budget; in fact this policy of economy\nwould have saved Mr. Truman from undeserved\ntinancial trouble which, through no fault of his,\ncame upon his former haberdashery store which I\nvisited a few weeks ago when in Kansas City.\nTHE PRESENT DANGER\nMr. and Mrs. Samuel sither of\nPhiladelphia. Mr. and Mrs. Alonzo\nShelton. Miss Grace Balfour, Miss\nEHa De p\u00abty. Misses Hilda and Ruth\nMayhew of Wilmington and Rich\nard Nottin s er of New York were\nthu week-end guests of jvir. and\n\n\"j\nattend( d a lu\ncheon m the Howl duPoni fv\u00bb\ny the Association of Graduate\nNurses on Wednesday afternoon to\nthe Red Cross nurses who have re\nturned from overseas.\n\nThe Farmers Produce Associa\ntion of Milford, through their\nboard of directors, last Saturday\nevening set the minimum price for\nwhich they will contract for toma\nto< r s a 1 41% cents a basket. This\nP rice 18 much more than the can\na re willing to contract for \u00abid\nthe latter men have been' asking\nthe farmers to grow and sell on the\nKd'o'r dlrWwrs \"\"hcl\u00e4ocia\ntion tomorrow evening a \u00abale\u00bb\nwm bc employed to handle\nhe tomatoes grown by the mem\nbers of the association\nTwo g have beeu i aunciie d at\nAbbott'S Shipyards in South Mil\nford <his week 0ne was P ut in\nthe water on Mondas 'and one y\u00abJ;\nh r r ^J wor e k he in New York harbor\nfor the Standard Oil Company.\nThis week the keels for five barges\nhaving a length of U. feet and\nb a,a bb r arc fo^the\nthe AbboU Company for the Stand\nthe difference. Such a borrowing policy is like a\nProhibitionist starting in to drink, or like a bank\nclerk starting to gamble, or like any family living\nbeyond its means. Once the habit starts, it is very\ndifficult to stop, and always ends in disaster.\nI was recently talking with Mr. Eugene W.,\nStetson, one of the best informed bankers in New\nYork, regarding the general business outlook. He\nstated that commodity prices could stabilize and\n\"if the business interests of\nemployment hold up\nthe country could have faith in (he Democratic Con\ngress now in session in Washington.\"\nwords, the recent decline in commodities and the\n\u2022companying increase In un employment, is largely;\ndue to a fear amongst thoughtful people that proper,\nIn otheri\n;h\nefforts will not bo made to reduce government\nspending and prevent further debt.\nWRITE YOUR CONGRESSMEN\nThercfore, if you readers of this column arc\ninterested in getting a fair price for your product\nand holding jobs for yourself and family. I earnestly\nurge that you write your Congressmen as follows:\n\"Please vote to reduce Government expenses so\n(hat it will bc unnecessary for Uncle Sam either to\nincrease taxes or to go into further debt.\" If your\nCongressmen will take your advice on this matter,\nthe decline in business at this time might be check\n<$)nslant decline in prices,\ned. But otherwise, a\nwages, and employment may be expected. It would\nbe the old story of trying to burn a candle at both\nends.\nLet's be frank. You know your Congressman.\nWould you employ him to run your own business?\nYet. you have elected him to run the greatest busi\nness in the world; and 1 say this very seriously. On\nthe other hand, your Congressman is anxious to\nplease a majority of his people who vote for him.\nThe labor interests are organized to push for a\ndeficit program. They seem to have no interest in\nbalancing the budget, but merely to make trouble.\nHence, the hope of the situation lies with independ\nent voters such as the farmers, small businessmen\nand unorganized workers. Perhaps, you will sug\ngest to your Congressmen that much of this desired\neconomy could be brought about without firing any\none.\u2014but by merely not replacing those government\nemployees who resign or die.\nMilford last Sunday created much\nexcitement and interest upon the\npart of the people of this section.\nThe machine was piloted by one\nman and came here from Pihia\ndeiphia. The pilot started for Har\nfW\u00c4\n\u00c4\nWvi.ion itoad to wnmingwn and\nhS\"i\u00c4 m \u00ab\u00c4 i\n.Jp er to\nJ J Aft lUling tho lank\nwnere ne was. Aiier miing me tai k\nuh Kasoltne he again left, this\ntime for Aberdeen, Md.. where he\ncan follow the river back to Har\nrisburg. The driver of the airplane\nwas advertising a flying school in to\nHarrisburg.\n\nTbe sixth annual commencement j\n0 i be \\jiiford Grammar School was i\nheld in the Armory la8t evening.!\nThe pupils w ho received cetrificates he\nof admission to the high school i i\nAn\u00eeia Be..-!\nn N t,u c c V ol\nCharles Edward ne\nnrvden Thomas Reed Draper. 1\nKk Hoards Grier Virgnia in\ni Hnil Hammond M^ry Grier Hai-1\nleit. Elva Mae Hall. Warren Henry\n|Hummell. George Vreeland Horton.\nj Sara Mildred Hill. Leah Betty Jor\nda v ma L emex\u00b0 n MvrUe whliey\nMarvel! James Mitsner, Harold\nPolk Nutter. Margaret Joyce Nunn, i\nMarjorie Frances Rosa. Frances\nAnn Russell. -.lar e 1 eUov\nstand^lvvroten. Mildred Elizabeth war-1\nWjoten.^Mi ar\nas\none,\nthe\nAs\nAn airplane which landed near\n\nI\nTNK\nHome A\nTown\np\u00a3PQPT\u20acP\nIN WASHINGTON\nWALTER SHCAO. WNLI Coi\nDefends Farm Plan\nY\u00b0UR Home Town Reporter can -1\n1 not hel P feel that at le f 8 i\nsome farm leaders are not being\n\nThat is, they are not being real-;\nistic from the standpoint of their j\nannounced reasons for opposition.\nnamely it regiments the farmers,\nit pays a subsidy to the farmers\nand it will be too costly.\nTo be realistic about the whole\nthing farmers must admit that they\nare being regimented today under\nthe present law and will be more\nregimented under the Hope-Aiken\nlaw which goes Into effect January\n1 unless congress changes it.\nrealistic in their opposition to the\nproposed new agricultural program\nof Secretary of Agriculture Bran\nnan.\nv\nThey are receiving a subsidy\ntoday under price support and\nwiU not only get price support\nbut direct subsidies in incen\ntive payments under the Hope\nAiken law. Insofar as costs are\nconcerned, nobody knows ex\nactly what the present law has\ncost, nobody knows or can guess\nwhat the Hope-Aiken law will\ncost and Secretary Brannan\nsays he doesn't know what his\nplan would cost, but believes it\nwiU cost no more than the\nAiken plan.\nThe department of agriculture\ndoes know, however, that prior to\n1926 insofar as the commodity\ncredit corporation is concerned, it\nhad made a little money on its op\nerations; but for an overall period\nfrom October 17, 1933, through\nMarch 31, 1949, the CCC showed\nnet loss on all its price support op\nerations of $322,574,785, of which\n$298,024,316 was lost on Irish po\ntatoes in the past three years.\ngovernrnent protection and govem\ngovenynau pruiecuun ana govern\nment help, and a guaranteed floor\nunder his prices, as it is for labor\nhave bargaining power and a\nfloor under his wages, or that busi\nness be protected with export sub\nsidies, with tariffs or other various\ngovernmental aids. And to get this\nhe must agree to certain\nthings-which is regimentation. And\naccep t s subsidies, directly\nn< \u00fc rec tly, sometimes both.\u2014And\nwhatevcr J' e D ac \u00abP\u00bbs cost, the tax\npayers. The Brannan plan may not\n.he best plan for agriculture,\nbut to \u00b0PP\u00b0 se on th es6 grounds ts.\nthis reporter's opinion, at least\nunrealistic,\nOne thing is certain, unless\nthe administration can in some\nway, not now apparent, get a\nerate ,ab brou h\n0 eal wuf\u00efeain be an^sMe^n\nf he 1950 b e _e, ections Activity\nnow is transferred to the senate\nwhere RepubUcans have the\nbal1 0,1 the ,abor biU mainly\nsenators Taft, Ives and Morse.\nFarmer Needs Aid\nWe like to picture our farmer\nthe lord of all he surveys, a\nrugged individualist beholden to no\naccepting no favors, taking his\nchances with the elements, the\npests, the drouths, the floods and\neconomic vagaries of the nation.\na matter of fact, however, those\ndays are gone forever.\nso\ni\nj\nI\nIn our modern complex econ\nomy it is historically true that\nthe farmer,\non his own\neventually will lose his shirt.\nHe always )ias and always will.\n\nIt is just as essential that he have\nor\nTough Selling Job\nThis reporter learned many years\nago that you cannot sell politics\nlike you sell soap. So Big Business,\nwhich employs big advertising\nagencies to sell soap and other com\nmodities, employs big agencies, to\nsell our democratic political sys\n_ t e ral P ubh c~and fails\nconvention c f the U.S* chambe^ct\ncommerce. We have the finest\nP oiitical system in the world, the\nfree enterprise system, but we\nhave a tough time selling our own\npeople on it. Yet we expect the\nVoice of America to sell it to the\nrest of me world.\nWith only 15 opposing votes, the\nfederal aid to education bill has\nswep t through the senate and is\nnow up for hearing before a house\ncommittee.\nIt authorizes an annual ex\npenditure of 300 million dollars\na year to states to equalize edu\ncational opportunities, the pay\nments to range from $5 to $29\nper child, depending on the\nstate income. Opposition was\nled by Senator Wherry of Ne\nbraska with ht Ip from Byrd of\nVirginia and Hrickcr of Ohio.\nFive freshmen senators voted for\nthe bill. Their predecessors in the\n80th congress were ag\u00e2inst it; they\nincluded Frear (D-Del.), Johnson\n(D-Tex.) t Hendrickson (R-N.J.),\nLong (D-La.) and Mundt, (R-S.D.),\nThere likely will be no tax in\ncrease at this session. Instead con\ngress may vote more money to\nthe treasury so they can put\nmore workers to collect more taxes\nunder the present law. Millions of\ntaxes annually are evaded because\nof lack of personnel to check\nturns. Treasury says.\non\nre\nT. B. Is M ^nace For\nIndia\nNEW DELHI WP) More than\nhalf a million people die of tuber\nculosis in India every year. Health\nMinister Fajakumari Amrit Kaur\nrecently reported.\nThe health minister frankly ad\niT5\nn|]i\ns\nm\nSocialized Education?\n-j RESID!2N t TRUMAN proposes\nthat the school, children of to\ndgy shaU fae the recip j ents 0 gov\nemmental care and protection dur*\ning their future years. The govern\nment will plan for them; will keep\nthem from want; wiU pay their\nmed i ca i 8n d hospital bills; will\neduca te them and their children?\nwill provide them with homes, and\nother essentials. The government\nwill plan and do for them what\ntheir progeny have in the past done\nfor themselves.\nIt is a glorious utopia that is\npromised, but what will it cost, and\nwho is to provide the funds needed\nto meet the elaborate welfare pro*\ngrams?\nGovernment experts who claim\nto be versed in such matters figure\nthe cost over the next 50 years will\nbe but the trifling sum of one and\na quarter trillion dollars. I have no\nidea of the meaning of such a sum.\nI have no conception of its magni\ntude. I doubt if any one other than,\npossibly, Professor Einstein, or the\nastronomers on Palomar mountain\nin California, could envision such\nfigures. In numerals, it looks like\nthis: $1,230,000,000,000. It is five\ntimes the amount of our present na\ntional debt.\nWhere Is such an amount of\nmoney to come from over the\nnext 50 years? Those responsi\nble for these wild welfare pro\ngrams propose to take it all\nright out of the pockets of\nthose who are today the school\nchildren of America. Each to\npay in proportion to what each\nmay earn, or what each may\nhave.\nIt is made to sound like a utopia,\nbut it does not provide for that\n\"something for nothing\" which It\nwould to promise. The school\nchildren of today and tomorrow\npay for the \"benefits\" they are\nglibly promised. They will pay\nalone for the \"hand outs\" they\nget, but they will pay the wages of\narmies of bureaucrats who will\nemployed to plan for those who\npay, and those who have will pay\nthose who have not.\nIn addition to the 1,250 billions\nthat constitute the one and a\nquarter trillion dollars they are to\npay for government planning and\ncare, they are also to continue to\npay, as their parents have, the\nlocal, county, state and federal tax\nes, with no indications of even a\nslight relief.\nThat one and a quarter tril\nlion dollars, equal to 1,250 bil\nlions, the school children are to\npay is expected to provide for\nold-age pensions, low rental\nhomes, socialized medicine,\nold-age and unemployment in\nsurance, and other things. For\naU of it, the bureaucrats will do\nthe planning, make the rules,\nand the children of today will\npay to the tune of one and a\nquarter trillion dollars. From\nthat sum the children, when\ngrown to manhood and woman\nhood may draw some meager\nsums provided it has not all\nbeen paid to the bureaucrats.\nEach year the cost is to mount\nto higher peaks, but, of course, the\nchild of today will be the wage\nearner of tomorrow, and more and\nmore is to be taken from the pay\nenvelope of those who may have a\npay envelope, to meet the increas\ning costs. It is Uncle Sam turned\nSanta Claus, providing the good\nlittle boys and girls deposit with\nhim, in advance, the toys he will\nreturn to them IF\u2014!\nSenator Taft asks the president\nand his followers to slide along a\nbit, so as to afford him a place on\nthe welfare platform. He insists\nthat unless the Republicans have a\nhand in the welfare handouts, the\nparty can have no chance of win\nning. The senator, too, believes all\nof the people can be fooled all of\nthe time. But former President\nHoover urges careful consideration\nof these welfare projects, and the\nterrific expense they will foist upon\nthose who are the children of today.\nTo him they are the fallacy the\nchildren will find them to be in the\nyears to come. Herbert Hoover is\nthe children's better friend,\nHow long will the American\npeople stand for these grandiose,\nan ridiculously expensive\nschemes, the only possible purpose\nof which is to attract votes. Let us\nhope we awaken before congress\nhas voted the payroll taxes that will\ntake from our children during the\nnext 50 years that trifling sum of\none and a quarter trillion dollars,\nmost of it to be spent for bureau\ncrat salaries. Such a sum will never\nbe paid, but the effort to collect\nwill break all of us.\nThe FBI is a department of the\nfederal government of which there\nire no complaints offered by the\npatriotic, law-abiding citizens.\ndoes a thorough job of securing\nevidence against criminals who\nhave violated federal laws, or who\nare disloyal to the American gov\nernment. It does not persecute,\nprosecute; it reports what it finds\nas the facts to the courts or to other\ndesignated authority. If a disloyal\ngovernment employee is not dis\ncharged it is not because the FBI\nhas not cooperated.\nmilled that it was impossible\nprevent the spread of this disease\nin India because of overcrowded\ncities and the scarcity of hospital\nbeds and sanatoria for T. B.\ntients.\nThe\nTuberculosis\nAssociation,\nwith the cooperation of the Health\nMinistry, is embarking on an\ntensive campaign of anti-tubercu\nlosis vaccination.","height":"25545","width":"20007"}}
